#                        COE5 RITUAL DATA IN MOD FORMAT
# 
# This file contains the ritual data for CoE5, extracted from the executable. 
# Although this file is not actually a mod, its contents adhere to CoE5's
# modding format in order to make it an optimal resource for modders.  That
# said, much of the information here can be useful to players, as well.
# 
# For modders, this file provides examples of how base game rituals can be
# built using modding commands (although some rituals in the base game do use
# some commands that are not available to modders) and templates that modders
# can use to create their own rituals.
# 
# For players, this file provides detailed information on how each ritual works
# and what it does.  In addition to being a time-saving reference, it also
# includes information that isn't visible anywhere in game, with examples
# including lists of possible results from summoning rituals, lists of source
# and destination units for promotion rituals, and the chances of successfully
# controlling certain summons.
# 
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 
#                           INFORMATION FOR PLAYERS
# 
# Everything to the right of a "#" (such as what you're reading now) is a
# comment, which means the game ignores it; it's there as a note for human
# readers (i.e. you).  I've provided comments on the right-hand side of most
# lines to explain what all the modding commands on the left actually do, so if
# you're not a modder, you can pretty much ignore most things on the left and
# just read the comments.
# 
# The major exceptions are:
# 
# -Lines beginning with newritual or selectritual.  The part between the "" is
# the name of the ritual; the comment with the number on the far right is the
# ritual's index number, which you can ignore.
# 
# -Lines beginning with descr.  The part between "" is the description shown in
# game when you right-click on the ritual.
# 
# -Commands whose names and meanings are especially obvious generally either
# don't get comments, or don't repeat the command name at the start of the
# comments, for the sake of brevity.  Two examples: "level 1" doesn't get a
# comment because the comment would be "# Level: 1"; "cost 0 25" gets the
# comment "# 25 Gold" instead of "# Cost: 25 Gold".
# 
# -Lines beginning with addstring.  Usually, these are found on summoning
# rituals, and the part between the "" (called the string) represents one
# possible result (a monster or group of monsters) that can appear when the
# summoning occurs.  Sometimes, one of a few special parenthetical expressions
# at the beginning of the string will give it a different meaning, in which
# case I'll explain that in a comment following the string.
# 
# If a line begins with "# fx" followed by a number, that means it's either a
# command that isn't accessible to modders, or I haven't taught the app to
# translate it yet (or both).  I present these as comments because they don't
# have mod command names that the game would recognize (so to adhere to the
# modding format, I need to tell it to ignore them), but the part that's
# actually intended for humans to read is the second comment, to the right. 
# Two examples:
# 
# fx1034               7 # [notplanereq]: Primal; cannot be cast on this plane.
# 
# fx1044               1 # Unhandled trait 1044 with argument 1.
# 
# The first example is a command that isn't accessible to modders.  You can
# safely ignore everything to the left of the second "#".  The word in [] is my
# guess at what Illwinter might call this command if they did make it
# accessible to modders.  Everything after that is my explanation of what it
# does; in this case, it prevents the ritual from being cast on the Primal
# Plane.
# 
# The second example is a command the app doesn't know how to translate (you
# can recognize these by the words "Unhandled" or "Unknown").  Unless you want
# to guess at their meanings, you can ignore these, other than to remember that
# there's some detail about the ritual that isn't explained yet.
# 
#                   ----------------------------------------
# 
#                                  Addstrings
# 
# At its simplest, a summoning string might look like this:
# 
# addstring     "Frost Fiend"
# 
# which means that if that string is the one randomly selected by the ritual,
# it will summon one Frost Fiend.  Toward the more complex end of the spectrum,
# a summoning string might look like this:
# 
# addstring     "c*Ancestral Chief & 1d3+1*Ancestral Lancer"
# 
# The "c*" means that an Ancestral Chief will be summoned and given commander
# status.  The "1d3+1*" means the game will roll a 3-sided die and add 1 to
# determine the number of Ancestral Lancers.  The two monster types are in the
# same string, joined by an "&", which indicates that if that string is
# randomly chosen, it will summon both an Ancestral Chief commander and 1d3+1
# Ancestral Lancers.
# 
#                                  ----------
# 
# Some summoning strings start with a number in parentheses, such as:
# 
# addstring     "(167)Anakite"
# 
# addstring     "(-110)Se'ir"
# 
# In these cases, the number represents a terrain, or if negative, one of the
# game's predefined terrain groups.  (167) means terrain 167, which is
# Ziggurat; (-110) means terrain group -110, which is desert-like terrains. 
# When a string begins with a parenthetical number, it means that string will
# only be included in the pool of possible random results when cast on the
# specified terrain; otherwise, it will be impossible.  When these terrain
# limiters occur, I provide comments following the string to explain them.
# 
#                                  ----------
# 
# A few summoning strings begin with the parenthetical expression "(!)", which
# applies special rules intended for magical familiars.  If the (!) string is
# the one selected, one of the following things will happen, in descending
# order of priority:
# 
# 1. If one or more of the specified units is present, one of them will be
# promoted to the unit defined after it in the Monster Data (e.g. Frog Familiar
# -> Magic Frog Familiar).
# 
# 2. Otherwise, if one or more of a promoted version of the specified unit is
# present, one of them will be randomly selected to learn a new level 1 spell. 
# If it already has all of the level 1 spells it can learn, it won't actually
# get anything, and the casting will have wasted AP and resources for nothing.
# 
# 3. If none of the specified unit or its promoted version are present, one of
# the specified units will be summoned.
# 
#                                  ----------
# 
# Another type of ritual that uses strings is the promotion ritual.  Rather
# than summoning a randomly selected string, a promotion ritual will take all
# of its addstring lines, momentarily excluding any that begin with a special
# parenthetical expression, and split them into pairs in the order they're
# listed.  Each pair is a promotion path; the first string of each pair is the
# kind of unit that can be promoted, while the second string is the kind of
# unit it will become.  For example, on a promotion ritual:
# 
# addstring     "Dwarf"
# addstring     "Rime Dwarf"
# addstring     "Dwarf Warrior"
# addstring     "Rime Warrior"
# 
# means that the ritual can turn a Dwarf into a Rime Dwarf or a Dwarf Warrior
# into a Rime Warrior.
# 
#                                  ----------
# 
# transformtarg rituals are another way of using strings.  These work similarly
# to promotion rituals, except that there's no need to specify the kind of
# units that can be changed, so instead every string (again, excluding any that
# begin with a special parenthetical expression) is a possible result of the
# transformation.  When the ritual is cast, one of the strings will be randomly
# selected, and the target will be changed into whatever monster that string
# specifies.  For example:
# 
# addstring     "Soldier Mirror"
# addstring     "Animal Mirror"
# 
# means that the target will become either a Soldier Mirror or an Animal
# Mirror, with a 50% chance of each.
# 
# There's also a variation of transformtarg (when its argument is 2, instead of
# 1) where if the selected transformation would reduce the target's ritual
# caster level, it will become the monster defined after that in the Monster
# Data, instead.  For example, the Necromancy ritual Blood Rite, which targets
# only the caster and has transformtarg 2 and:
# 
# addstring     "Vampire"
# 
# is saying that if it's cast by a Necromancer, he will become a Vampire (since
# they both have Necromancy ritual power, level 2), but if it's cast by a Grand
# Necromancer (who has level 3), he will instead become a Vampire Count (which
# is also level 3), since that's the next monster after Vampire in the Monster
# Data.
# 
#                                  ----------
# 
# One last way that strings not beginning with a special parenthetical
# expression are used in the base game's Ritual Data is for levelupmon rituals.
# Seen only in various Warlock Pact rituals, levelupmon works a lot like the
# normal version of transformtarg, except the target will only be changed to
# the monster specified in the string if the target's ritual power level is
# below the value of levelupmon.  For example, the first version of the ritual
# Earth Pact, which targets only the caster and has levelupmon 2 and:
# 
# addstring     "Warlock of Earth"
# 
# is saying that it will only change the caster into a Warlock of Earth if he
# isn't already a Warlock of Earth (level 2) or Great Warlock of Earth (level
# 3).
# 
#                                  ----------
# 
# Several times above, I've mentioned special parenthetical expressions with
# which a string can begin, which will change its meaning.  These are (+), (-),
# and (&).
# 
# (-) is the one seen most often, and it means that the string will only be
# used to tell one of the commands beginning with "nomon" one of the kinds of
# monsters that should prevent the ritual from being cast.
# 
# For example, the Senator ritual Coronation is a promotion ritual with
# nomonworldreq and the following addstrings:
# 
# addstring     "(-)Emperor"
# addstring     "(-)Dark Emperor"
# addstring     "(-)God Emperor"
# addstring     "(-)God Emperor of the Underworld"
# addstring     "(-55)Senator"
# addstring     "Dark Emperor"
# addstring     "Senator"
# addstring     "Emperor"
# 
# The first four begin with (-), so each of them is telling nomonworldreq one
# kind of unit to look for: if an Emperor, Dark Emperor, God Emperor, and / or
# God Emperor of the Underworld exists anywhere in the world, the ritual cannot
# be cast.
# 
# Note that the fifth string does not start with (-); it starts with (-55), so
# it's a terrain limiter, as explained earlier.  This means it's actually one
# of the pairs of strings used by promotion, so those last four strings are
# saying: if cast on a damned capital (terrain -55), change a Senator into a
# Dark Emperor; otherwise, change a Senator into an Emperor.
# 
# (+) is only seen in the base game in Ritual of Scourge Mastery, but it can
# actually be used with any ritual that uses a command beginning with "nomon". 
# If the monster in a string beginning with (+) satisfies the condition of the
# "nomon" command, it disables all (-) strings after it.
# 
# For our example, Ritual of Scourge Mastery has level 1, nomonmasteryreq, and
# the following addstrings:
# 
# addstring     "(+)Scourge King"
# addstring     "(-)Scourge Lord"
# 
# This means that normally, it cannot be cast if you have a Scourge Lord, but
# there are two exceptions: first, as is normal for nomonmasteryreq, if the
# caster is higher level than the minimum needed to cast the ritual (so, level
# 2+; i.e. a Scourge Lord or Scourge King), he can cast it (but minimum level
# casters, meaning Scourge Heralds, still can't); second, because of the (+)
# string, if you have a Scourge King, then having a Scourge Lord no longer
# prevents anyone from casting it (so even Scourge Heralds can now cast it).
# 
# Finally, (&) strings are used only to tell minmonreq, monworldreq, or
# monplayerreq commands which kinds of monsters can satisfy their requirements.
# (&) is to those commands what (-) is to "nomon" commands.
# 
#                   ----------------------------------------
# 
#                          Summoning String Selection
# 
# Barring the presence of sum0chance (and the other sum[x]chance commands) or
# sum0snow, all summoning strings are equally likely to be chosen as the result
# of the summons.  The game appears to simply count the number of strings (or
# the number remaining after these commands) and roll a die of that size to
# pick which to use.
# 
# When sum0chance is present (or sum0snow, if the ritual is cast on a snowy
# square), it receives a separate d100 roll to see whether to choose the first
# string, before moving on to sum1chance or the remaining strings.  In this
# way, sum0chance (or sum0snow) is exactly as likely to succeed as its argument
# (the percentage chance shown for it) says.
# 
# sum1chance, on the other hand, is only used when sum0chance has already been
# used in the same ritual.  sum1chance, too, receives a separate d100 roll to
# see whether it triggers, but it occurs after the check for sum0chance, and
# only if that check fails.  As a result, sum1chance is actually less likely to
# succeed than its argument suggests.  In keeping with basic probability, the
# actual percentage chance for sum1chance to succeed would be modeled by this
# formula:
# 
# (1 - (sum0chance / 100)) * sum1chance
# 
# The other sum[x]chance commands work the same way, with each higher number
# becoming even less likely to succeed than its argument indicates, because all
# earlier checks must fail first.
# 
# Let's break down the most complicated example in the ritual data.  The ritual
# Summon Lesser Beings has sum0chance 5, sum1chance 5, and sum2chance 10 with
# the following strings:
# 
# addstring     "Bakeneko"
# addstring     "c*Tengu Weapon Master"
# addstring     "c*Mujina"
# addstring     "2d3*Kappa"
# addstring     "Karasu Tengu"
# addstring     "1d3*Konoha Tengu"
# 
# The actual chance of the first string, Bakeneko, is just the 5% specified by
# sum0chance 5.
# 
# To get the actual percentage chance of the second string, Tengu Weapon
# Master, we need to convert the percentage chance of getting the first string
# (5%) to a probability (meaning, divide by 100), then subtract it from 1 to
# find the probability of failing to get the first string.  Then we multiply
# that by the stated chance of sum1chance to get the actual chance.  Like so:
# 
# (1 - (sum0chance / 100)) * sum1chance
# (1 - (5 / 100)) * 5 = 4.75%
# 
# To get the actual percentage chance of the third string, we follow a similar
# process, only this time, we need to multiply sum2chance by the probability of
# failing to get both the first and second strings:
# 
# (1 - ((5 + 4.75) / 100)) * 10 = 9.025%
# 
# That leaves us with the last three strings, and since we're out of the
# sum[x]chance commands, all remaining strings split the remaining probability
# equally between them.  Thus, the percentage chance of each of the last three
# strings is:
# 
# (100% - (5% + 4.75% + 9.025%)) / 3 =  27.075%
# 
# You can use similar means to calculate the actual chance of any string in any
# summoning ritual.
# 
# One final note on the subject of summoning chances: the ritual Banquet for
# the Dead has sum0chance 50, but only one string, which may leave you
# wondering what to expect when casting it.  In my testing, it appears that
# sum0chance 50 has no effect on this ritual; the one string is summoned every
# time it is cast.  I assume there is a safeguard requiring that a ritual have
# at least two strings before sum0chance can take effect, and that this is the
# reason sum0chance is harmless in Banquet for the Dead.  As a side note, the
# inclusion of sum0chance 50 in Banquet for the Dead looks to me like a copy-
# paste error from Grand Blood Feast.
# 
# Similarly, the ritual Summon Storm Giant has sum0chance 66, but only one
# string.  Again, it always summons the one string, and again, it appears to be
# a copy-paste error, this time from Summon Champion of Air.
# 
#                   ----------------------------------------
# 
#                           Unusual Summoning Rituals
# 
# Most summoning rituals actually just create new monsters, rather than moving
# and repossessing existing monsters.  However, there are a number of rituals
# that include strings with monsters that have the "unique" trait.  Most of
# these monsters are one-of-a-kind and created at the start of the game.  When
# one of them is selected by a summoning ritual, the game checks if they're
# available and if so, teleports them to the caster.  If that monster isn't
# available, the ritual will simply fail with the message "No one answered the
# summoning", but the costs of the ritual will already have been paid.  This
# can make fishing for uniques even more expensive as the pool of available
# uniques dwindles.
# 
#                                  ----------
# 
# Rather than using strings, the two versions each of Minor Animal Summoning
# and Major Animal Summoning use the specpow command to somehow determine the
# types and numbers of monsters to summon.  Certain terrains (including at
# least Ancient Forests, Forests, Jungles, Deserts, and Spider Thickets) affect
# what can be summoned, but the exact mechanics of these rituals remain
# mysterious.
# 
#                                  ----------
# 
# The ritual Call Primal Being uses another unique summoning mechanic instead
# of strings.  When cast, it searches the Primal Plane for all eligible
# monsters, then randomly chooses one of them to teleport to the caster's
# location and changes ownership of it to the casting player.
# 
# In my tests, the complement of eligible monsters present at the start of the
# game was largely identical from game to game, varying only in the number of
# Ents and the types of Beholders:
# 
# 8x Beholder
# 1x Horned God
# 1x Hammer God
# 1x God of the Seasons
# 1x God of War
# 1x Goddess of the Sacred Spring
# 1x God of the Sea
# 1x Thrice Horned Boar
# 1x Rams-Headed Serpent
# 3x Hooded Spirit (one of each of the three types)
# 7-15x Ent
# 
# Each of the Beholders has an equal chance (47.5%) to be either of the two
# types, with a 5% chance to be an Elder Beholder instead.
# 
# The Beholders and Ents are mortal; once killed, they're gone for good, and in
# my tests, no new ones ever spawned.  The other Primal Beings are immortal
# unless killed on the Primal Plane; if killed anywhere else, they'll respawn
# on the Primal Plane, revert to being controlled by the independents, and be
# eligible to summon again.
# 
# If no eligible monsters remain on the Primal Plane, casting Call Primal Being
# fails with the message "No one answered the summoning", but still wastes AP
# and Herbs.
# 
#                   ----------------------------------------
# 
#                     Control Chance For Summoning Rituals
# 
# The base chance to control each type of monster summoned by a ritual is
# determined as follows:
# 
# 1. If the ritual does not contain the defctrl command, control cannot fail.
# 
# 2. Otherwise, if the monster has a defined ctrlchance, use that.
# 
# 3. Otherwise, use the ritual's defctrl.
# 
# For rituals with the varcost command, the base control chance is further
# modified by the Sacrifice Level (SL) used to cast the ritual.  For SL 0 to
# 100, the following formula is how final control chance is determined:
# 
#  final_control_chance = base_control_chance * (resources_spent / cost)
# 
# For example, with a base control chance of 60% and a cost of 40 sacrifices,
# you could spend 30 sacrifices (0.75 times normal) for a 45% final control
# chance (also 0.75 times normal).
# 
# Newly in CoE5, increasing Sacrifice Level above 100 gives diminishing
# benefits to control chance.  The exact formula is unknown, but the game
# manual provides two points: when spending 1.5 times base cost, final control
# chance will be 1.33 times base control chance; and when spending 2 times base
# cost, final control chance will be 1.5 times base control chance.  Thus, the
# further above 100 Sacrifice Level rises, the less cost-effective it becomes.
# 
# For rituals with varcost 100 (which in the base game means the Demonology and
# Bakemono summoning rituals), Sacrifice Level can be set anywhere from 0 to
# 200.  If you have a powerful enough army to fight uncontrolled summons with
# negligible casualties, SL 100 is the most cost-effective choice.  Otherwise,
# it's often a good idea to maximize control chance, especially if final
# control chance can reach 100%.  Since SL 200 will give 1.5 times base control
# chance, the lowest base control chance that can reach 100% final control
# chance on a varcost 100 ritual is 67%.
# 
# On the other hand, while Sacrifice Level 0 and its guarantee that the
# summoned monsters will attack you may sound like a bad idea, it can be very
# useful in some cases.  If you have charm or enslavement abilities, you may be
# able to take control of some of the summoned monsters without having paid
# anything for them.  Further, some summoned monsters (most notably those of
# the Summon Demon Lieutenant ritual) can spawn with items.  If you can charm,
# enslave, or kill them with negligible casualties, you can farm items at no
# cost by using SL 0.
# 
# For rituals with varcost 50 (which in the base game means the Witchery
# summoning rituals), Sacrifice Level can be set anywhere from 50 to 150. 
# Since SL 150 will give 1.33 times base control chance, the lowest base
# control chance that can reach 100% final control chance on a varcost 50
# ritual is 75 or 76%, depending on how the game rounds.
# 
# As with SL 0 on varcost 100 rituals, SL 50 on varcost 50 rituals can be
# useful.  If you can reliably charm or enslave the summoned monsters, you may
# be able to get them at half price by using SL 50.
# 
# As a final note, when a string contains multiple types of monsters, my tests
# suggest that the game rolls only once for control, using the base control
# chance of only the first monster in the string (its ctrlchance if it has one
# and the value isn't 0; otherwise the ritual's defctrl).  If the control roll
# succeeds, all monsters in the string will be controlled; if it fails, all
# will be uncontrolled.  The only example of this in the base game is the
# ritual Deep Rising, which includes the following:
# 
# addstring     "c*Basalt Prince & 2d6*War Shambler & 4d6*Deep One Warrior"
# 
# Because Deep Rising has defctrl 66, the base control chance for any monster
# without its own defined ctrlchance will be 66%.  In the above string, this is
# true of Basalt Prince and Deep One Warrior.  However, War Shambler has
# ctrlchance 80, meaning its base control chance is 80%.  Because the game only
# rolls for control once for the entire string and only the first monster's
# control chance matters, the Basalt Prince's use of defctrl 66 gives the
# entire above string a base control chance of 66%, effectively making the War
# Shamblers harder to control than they would otherwise be.
# 
# Longtime readers may recall that it used to be the highest control chance
# that mattered, not the first.  This behavior appears to have changed sometime
# between when I first tested it in CoE4 v4.18 and when I tested it again in
# CoE5 v5.22.
# 
#                   ----------------------------------------
# 
# At the end of this file are a number of ritual descriptions unaccompanied by
# any other data.  A few of these are simply unused descriptions, but most are
# used by the Ceremonies of the Voice of El.  The Ceremonies have no data there
# beyond their names and descriptions because their data is not found with that
# of the other rituals.  Where it is and how it's encoded remains unknown.
# 
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 
#                           INFORMATION FOR MODDERS
# 
# The CoE5 modding manual is a very useful source of information, and I'd
# consider it required reading for anyone who wants to mod CoE5, as well as a
# recommended read for anyone who is at all interested in how the game works. 
# That said, in working on the ritual data, I have encountered a few
# discrepancies and omissions from the modding manual.
# 
# Throughout this file, I have written comments explaining each command, with
# the goal of saving the reader from as much cross-referencing with the modding
# manual as possible.  Many of these comments are copied directly from the
# modding manual, and others are adapted slightly to suit my needs.  However,
# there are a few commands whose descriptions there I have found to be
# incomplete or inaccurate.  In any case of conflict between my comments and
# the modding manual, I have written what I believe to be correct.  Of
# particular note are these commands:
# 
# defctrl (with an argument of 997)
# apcost (with a negative argument)
# unfollowtarg
# rebateterr20
# 
# defctrl 997 is never mentioned in the modding manual; it is a special value
# with three effects: 1. control of summonings cannot fail, 2. log text is
# "raised" instead of "summoned", and 3. sound played is digrydoo.smp
# (didgeridoo) instead of orchhit.smp (summoning).
# 
# When the apcost command is used, the ritual's actual AP cost will be apcost's
# argument plus one.  The modding manual doesn't explicitly mention that apcost
# can take a negative argument, which it can.  Thus, apcost can be used to make
# a ritual cost no AP or even refund AP.  E.g. apcost -1 will give actual AP
# cost 0, and apcost -2 will refund 1 AP.
# 
# unfollowtarg does not, as the modding manual states, make anyone stop
# following the target.  Rather, it makes the target stop following anyone.
# 
# Contrary to the modding manual, the game's own interface, and the number
# included in the name of the command, rebateterr20 actually reduces ritual
# cost by 25%, not 20%.  This is probably a bug.
# 
#                   ----------------------------------------
# 
#                             Ritual Modding Maxima
# 
# CoE5 has reserved space for a total of 3000 rituals, including those from the
# base game and all simultaneously activated mods.  This gives us a rough
# ballpark of how many rituals can be added by mods (3000 minus the number
# reserved for the base game), but not an exact number.  Illwinter reserve more
# slots for base game rituals than are currently in use, so that they can add
# new rituals in future updates without breaking every saved game that uses
# mods with new rituals, but to my knowledge, they haven't stated exactly how
# many ritual slots they've reserved for the base game.  Probably there's room
# for mods to add at least 2000 rituals; I very much doubt there's room for
# more than 2400.
# 
# Each ritual's name can be up to 48 bytes long.  How many characters that is
# depends on how many bytes it takes to express each character in UTF-8
# encoding.  Usually, it's one or two bytes per character, so that means 24 to
# 48 characters.
# 
# Each ritual has reserved space for 4 instances of the cost command (you can
# use less, but not more).
# 
# Each ritual has reserved space for 1 (and only 1) each of the following
# commands: ritpow, level, and terr.  Each ritual also has reserved space for
# each of the 11 (at the time I write this) commands within the Ritual Learning
# Difficulty sub-section in the modding manual.
# 
# Each ritual has room for 48 addstring commands.  Each of those strings (the
# part between "") can be up to 256 bytes long.  Again, how many characters
# that is depends on how many bytes it takes to express each character in UTF-8
# encoding.
# 
# Each ritual has room for 14 fx commands.  From the Summoning Commands header
# to the end of the Ritual Modding section of the modding manual, expect every
# command there that has not already been mentioned here to use up one of the
# ritual's fx command slots.
# 
